e for the family and that is the root cause of all frustrations.So it is good to be concerned than getting attached.&gt;&gt;\n\n\nWe can talk of love for and attachment to God. But, how do you think of and love the Supreme Cosmic Being who is in every being and in every atom and yet beyond our conception and imagination? How can you love, become attached to and serve what you cannot even conceive or fathom?\n\n\nAs people around us are the limited manifestations of God, isn&#39;t serving them a way to serve God and loving them a way to love God?!\n\nHowever, your point about expecting something in return is correct. When we do something for someone, we consciously or sub-consciously expect something in return (at least gratitude or even acknowledgment, if nothing else). But, if one has this attitude, it can extend to God too. One can worship God and do many rituals and expect something in return even there (&quot;moksha&quot; or other kinds of spiritual progress).\n\nWhy can&#39;t the ability to do things without expecting something in return be developed and honed while doing things for others?\n\nDetachment is different from either aversion or a fear of attachment! Detachment implies neither a dry mental state devoid of emotion nor a grudging discharge of responsibility.\n\nIsn&#39;t it possible to look at people as limited manifestations of God, who are worshiped/served in different ways by offering different services, offer those services thinking of them as limited manifestations of God, taking pleasure in their enjoyment of the services offered by you, and yet not expect anything in return, not even gratitude or acknowledgement? Isn&#39;t that a beginning to the development of detachment?\n\nIsn&#39;t the entire world you interact with is a limited manifestation of God and aren&#39;t all your actions towards the world your offerings to God?\n\nBest regards,\nNarasimha\n--------\nAstrology & Spirituality Resources: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org\n--------\n\n&g